Fifteen century Germany
The Particular of the Wolves has, like much of the Church, been falling apart in slow motion.
Due to the stronger traditions of the wolves, the Roma have been loathe to intrude on Germanic lands before. In the past, the wolves have been vicious opponents, killing humans and their own that invade their lands - and acting as mercenaries for other nobles. But the Black Death has killed so many that the wolves can barely work and hold their own lands.
The wolves and humans never did more than tolerate each other. But finding one in the lands of the others is rarer than a good harvest these days.
Slowly, the Roma invade. They are not an army like the Huns or Turks. And inside some of their travelling communities, the humans and wolves live side by side.
The only surviving son of a farmer has returned home from soldiering to bury his father, and the Roma are camped on the fields. He grabs a blade, and marches in the night to the closest wagon.
On the other side of the camp he can see the nearby villagers filing in and out, carrying cookery and other items.
He knocks at the varicolored door, painted with stars and moons. A female voice, non-human, says to enter.
Across from him is a wolfess dealing strange cards onto a small table. She deals another.
"Sit, child of the blade. I knew you'd come. Share water and oath with me."
